## 7. Blockchain Integration

### 7.1 Local Development Setup

| Component | Tool | Details |
|---|---|---|
| Local Blockchain | **Ganache** | Provides 10 pre-funded Ethereum accounts; runs on `http://127.0.0.1:7545` |
| Contract Development | **Hardhat** | Compile, test, and deploy Solidity contracts |
| Frontend Integration | **ethers.js v6** | Connect to Ganache, send transactions, read contract state |

### 7.2 Hardhat Configuration

```js
// hardhat.config.js
require("@nomicfoundation/hardhat-toolbox");

module.exports = {
  solidity: "0.8.19",
  networks: {
    ganache: {
      url: "http://127.0.0.1:7545",
      // Ganache provides accounts automatically
    },
  },
};
```

### 7.3 Contract Deployment Script

```js
// scripts/deploy.js
const hre = require("hardhat");

async function main() {
  const Voting = await hre.ethers.getContractFactory("Voting");
  const voting = await Voting.deploy();
  await voting.waitForDeployment();
  console.log("Voting contract deployed to:", await voting.getAddress());
}

main().catch(console.error);
```

**Deployment command:**
```bash
npx hardhat run scripts/deploy.js --network ganache
```

### 7.4 Wallet Assignment Strategy

Each registered student is assigned a unique Ganache account:

1. Ganache provides **10 accounts** by default (configurable to more)
2. On student registration, the API assigns the next unused account
3. The account address and private key are stored server-side
4. When voting, the API signs the transaction on behalf of the student using their assigned private key

> [!WARNING]
> In a production system, users would connect their own wallets (e.g., MetaMask). For this mini-project, server-side wallet management simplifies the UX but is **not secure for production use**.

### 7.5 Frontend ↔ Contract Interaction

```js
// lib/contract.js
